\begin{abstract}
Hearing impairment affects hundreds of millions of people worldwide and significantly limits their ability to perceive and interpret critical environmental sounds. Conventional assistive devices, such as hearing aids and cochlear implants, primarily focus on sound amplification and do not provide sufficient contextual or spatial awareness. This paper presents a wearable, non-prosthetic assistive system designed to enhance situational awareness for individuals with hearing loss by integrating multiple audio processing capabilities into a unified framework. The proposed system combines environmental sound recognition, sound source localization, and real-time speech-to-text transcription using a multi-microphone array and a lightweight embedded platform. Audio signals are processed through a pipeline that includes preprocessing, feature extraction, and machine learning-based inference. The extracted information is conveyed to the user via augmented reality (AR) visual feedback and haptic alerts, enabling intuitive interpretation of surrounding acoustic events. The paper details the system design, hardware integration, and software architecture, followed by an experimental investigation of its core components. Results demonstrate the feasibility of combining semantic and spatial audio understanding within a single assistive platform, highlighting its potential to improve safety, communication, and overall quality of life for hearing-impaired users.

\end{abstract}
\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Hearing impairment; Assistive technology; Sound recognition; Sound source localization; Speech-to-text; Wearable system; Embedded AI
\end{IEEEkeywords}

