\section{Introduction}
Hearing impairment is a widespread global health challenge that affects millions of individuals and significantly impacts their ability to interact safely and independently with their environment. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), over 430 million people worldwide experience disabling hearing loss, a number expected to increase in the coming decades\footnote{Deafness and hearing loss, Available: \url{https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/deafness-and-hearing-loss}. Accessed on 25-01-2026.}. One of the most critical challenges faced by hearing-impaired individuals is the inability to perceive important environmental sounds such as alarms, approaching vehicles, or verbal warnings, which can lead to serious safety risks. And existing assistive technologies, including hearing aids and cochlear implants, primarily focus on amplifying sound signals. However, these solutions do not provide sufficient contextual understanding of the acoustic environment, nor do they offer information about the direction of sound sources. As a result, users may still struggle to interpret their surroundings, especially in complex or noisy environments.

Recent advances in artificial intelligence and embedded systems have enabled the development of smarter assistive solutions that go beyond amplification. Techniques such as audio event recognition~\cite{Prashanth2023}, speaker recognition~\cite{Youssef2017}, speech-to-text conversion~\cite{Ahlawat2025}, and acoustic source localization~\cite{Youssef2015} have shown promising results when applied individually. However, most existing systems focus on a single functionality and lack an integrated framework that combines semantic and spatial audio understanding into a unified assistive experience. In parallel, advances in fields like wearable technologies~\cite{Said2021} and virtual and augmented reality~\cite{Awadhi2018} are enabling the development of efficient assistive systems.

This work proposes a wearable assistive system that enhances situational awareness for hearing-impaired users by integrating three key capabilities: environmental sound recognition, sound source localization, and real-time speech-to-text transcription. The system utilizes a multi-microphone array and a lightweight embedded platform to process audio in real time and deliver feedback through augmented reality (AR) visualization and haptic alerts. Through these tasks, the system transforms acoustic information into intuitive visual and tactile cues, enabling users to perceive, interpret, and respond to surrounding sounds and speech in real time, thereby improving their environmental awareness, communication effectiveness, and overall quality of life. The paper shows the design of the system and highlights the implementation and experimental investigation of its most relevant parts.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:related_work} shows recent related work that addressed similar objectives. Section~\ref{sec:design} shows the design of the proposed system, %followed by implementation aspects in Section~\ref{sec:implementation}. 
Section~\ref{sec:investigation} shows an experimental investigation of key components of the proposed system, followed by a discussion and a conclusion in Section~\ref{sec:discussion} and Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} respectively.

