\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related_work}
Across the literature, different work have been proposed for assisting persons with hearing losses without using prosthetic devices such as hearing aids and cochlear implants. These systems relied on different technologies, including machine learning, signal processing, augmented reality displays, internet of things and others to perform different tasks in different paradigms. 

Speech recognition was addressed in~\cite{Antonia2021} where a speech to tactile translation system was presented, enabling speech perception through vibration. Also in~\cite{Senaha2025}, speech recognition was performed and text was displayed on smart glasses. While some speech recognition systems were general and used publicly available libraries, others focused on detecting specific words~\cite{Adnan2021}, operated in a speaker-dependent context~\cite{Yaganoglu2021} or focused on children with hearing losses~\cite{Chandrashekar2025}. Sounds other than speech have also been addressed in works such as~\cite{Karroum2025} where detection of relevant sounds like horns and alarms was performed, and~\cite{Tang2025} where other sounds like fire alarms, boiling water and knocking were addressed. Also, emergency sound detection was addressed in~\cite{Munasinghe2025} and~\cite{Tan2025}. 

Another task in the non-prosthetic assistance of persons with hearing losses is sound source localization, allowing to estimate the location of sound sources which can be relevant to the users in different situations. The work presented in~\cite{Tang2025} performed localization using a 4-microphone array, estimating the direction of arrival of the sound. Microphone arrays were also used in~\cite{Senaha2025}%,~\cite{Rathna2024}
and~\cite{Tan2025} for localization. Additionally, the recognition of the speaker's emotion was addressed in different work such as~\cite{Gupta2025} and~\cite{ubur2025}, helping the persons with hearing losses to understand the emotional states of the persons they interact with and enriching their understanding of the acoustic environment. Other tasks have also been addressed in the literature, such as sign language recognition%~\cite{talaat2024real, 
~\cite{Alabdullah2025}. 

Across the literature, different paradigms in which the tasks above have been performed can be found. Most of the work relied on wearable designs embedding the different components and functionalities with the aim of providing the tackled information in comfort and efficiency. In~\cite{Goyal2023}, a wearable system through which caregivers could send haptic signals was presented. Another system was presented in~\cite{Buhat}, consisting of a headband and a wristwatch for sound classification and multimodal alerts. Another device embedding smart glasses and microphones was presented in~\cite{Matsuo2024} and a glove-based system was shown in~\cite{Abhiram2024}. However, non-wearable mobile platforms have also been used in the literature. This includes different examples such as the ones shown in~\cite{Lee2021} and~\cite{Muyi2023}, robotic platforms inspired by hearing dogs, other robotic platforms~\cite{Tang2025} and mobile phone-based approaches~\cite{Fukui2022, Mahmud2023}. Additionally, social robotics~\cite{Youssef2021SocialRobot} have the potential to be used in this domain.

Despite significant progress in assistive technologies, existing solutions remain limited in providing a comprehensive understanding of the acoustic environment. Most prior work focuses on a single task, such as sound classification or speech recognition, without integrating spatial awareness or multimodal feedback. Furthermore, few systems are implemented as real-time wearable solutions on resource-constrained embedded platforms. Additionally, support for non-English languages, particularly Arabic dialects such as the Kuwaiti dialect, remains underexplored. This gap highlights the need for an integrated, real-time assistive system that combines semantic sound understanding, spatial localization, and user-friendly feedback mechanisms within a single wearable platform.

