\section{System Design}
\label{sec:design}
The proposed non-prosthetic assistive system for hearing-impaired users is wearable and designed to enhance environmental awareness. It integrates a hardware–software architecture that performs three core tasks: speech-to-text (STT), sound recognition, and sound source localization, enabling real-time situational awareness through visual and haptic feedback.
%\subsection{ High-Level Design}
At a high level, the system captures environmental sounds using a multi-channel microphone array. The captured audio is processed through parallel pipelines to extract both semantic information (sound type) and spatial information (sound direction). The processed outputs are then delivered to the user via an augmented reality (AR) display and vibration alerts.

\subsection{ Hardware Design}
The hardware architecture is centered around the Raspberry Pi 5, %which serves as the main processing unit 
responsible for executing AI inference tasks. Environmental sounds are captured using the ReSpeaker XVF3800 4-Mic Array\footnote{Getting Started with reSpeaker XVF3800 USB Mic Array $\vert$ Seeed Studio Wiki. Available: \url{https://wiki.seeedstudio.com/respeaker_xvf3800_introduction/}. Accessed on 28-03-2026.}, which consists of four MEMS microphones arranged in a circular configuration, enabling 360° multi-channel audio acquisition required for accurate sound localization.
The system provides feedback through two main output components:
\begin{itemize}
  \item A web interface, which displays sound labels, transcribed speech, and directional indicators on any device connected to the same Wi-Fi network
  \item A vibration motor module (connected via GPIO18), which generates haptic alerts for serious sounds such as sirens
\end{itemize}

