\subsubsection{Sound Recognition}

Mono audio frames are buffered into 0.96-second segments and converted to 64-band log-mel spectrograms using FFT and a Mel filter bank. These spectrograms are passed to the pre-trained YAMNet model\footnote{\url{https://github.com/Jaskaran197/YAMNET-Sound-Classification-python}}  to classify environmental sounds, outputting a sound label and confidence 
score for each segment.

\subsubsection{Speech-to-Text (STT)}
The speech-to-text module processes mono speech signals captured by the ReSpeaker using the Faster-Whisper speech recognition model for Arabic, including the Kuwaiti dialect\footnote{\url{https://github.com/SYSTRAN/faster-whisper}}. The input is verbal speech, which is converted into transcription text in real time and then displayed on the AR screen.In addition to the Arabic speech-to-text module, an English speech-to-text module was developed using the Faster-Whisper model. The system processes speech input captured from the microphone and converts it into transcription text in real time. The output is then displayed on the AR interface, supporting continuous operation.



\subsubsection{Multimodal Fusion and Output:}
The outputs from all modules: sound-label, transcript-text, confidence-score, and direction-angle, are combined in a multimodal fusion stage. The final result is designed to be displayed through AR visualization (icons, text, and directional arrows) as illustrated in Figure~\ref{fig:new}, while the vibration motor is triggered for critical alerts. This ensures that the user receives a "unified representation" of the acoustic event. 
