\subsection{Sound Recognition}
The sound recognition functionality was implemented as a core component of the system, enabling real-time environmental sound classification and direct conversion into text with negligible latency. The system integrates the YAMNet deep learning model, which is capable of classifying more than 500 environmental sound categories. Our experiments focused on experimental evaluation of the YAMNet model under specific testing conditions, with emphasis on performance rather than internal architecture.
The experimental setup was designed to simulate real-world usage scenarios for hearing-impaired users, including variations in sound type, distance, and environmental context. Testing was conducted in an approximately $6\times 5\times 2.8 m$ indoor environment% with approximate dimensions of 6 meters (length), 5 meters (width), and an estimated height of approximately 2.8 meters
%, representing a small enclosed space
, where both near-field and far-field sound sources were considered. 
The results demonstrate that the system reliably detects human speech with high confidence values ranging from 0.97 to 1.0, while silence is correctly identified with a confidence of 1.0 in the absence of sound.
