\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
Regarding sound source localization, recent studies have explored various approaches. In ~\cite{Tang2025}, a TDOA-based algorithm achieved high accuracy with an azimuth error within ±5° at a distance of 2 meters; however, it was limited to five discrete angles, restricting resolution. Similarly, ~\cite{Senaha2025} evaluated directions from 15° to 165° with 15° increments but relied on a single recording setup. In contrast, ~\cite{Tan2025} proposed a wearable system with only coarse directional outputs (front, back, left, right), lacking precise angular estimation. In this work, Table~1 presents results from a new recording (S2) not included in training. The system achieved good accuracy using both GCC-Strength and GCC-TDOA. Compared to previous studies, it provides finer angular resolution with 15° increments, demonstrating improved robustness and directional precision.

In sound recognition system, results demonstrate the  performs effectively under realistic indoor conditions. High confidence values for human speech and silence indicate reliable differentiation between acoustic events, which is essential for assistive applications. The system consistently classified various sound categories, including human activities, object-related sounds, and animal sounds. Sounds closer to the microphone produced higher confidence scores than distant sounds, reflecting the influence of signal strength and environmental factors. Minor misclassifications occurred due to similarities in acoustic features; however, these were associated with low confidence values and did not significantly impact overall performance. Overall, the system provides reliable, real-time sound recognition, supporting its suitability for enhancing environmental awareness for hearing-impaired users.

For Arabic speech-to-text, the child’s voice was translated less accurately than the adult’s due to less clear articulation, making recognition more difficult. Additionally, translating individual words was faster and more accurate than processing longer sentences, which require more time. The system handled the Kuwaiti dialect reasonably well, though some spelling errors were observed, indicating the need for further improvement. The system is suitable for assisting deaf and hearing-impaired individuals, particularly due to its quick response to short warning words. Therefore, focusing on short phrases and keywords is recommended. Improving word recognition and spelling accuracy remains necessary.


