\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
This paper presented a wearable, non-prosthetic assistive system designed to enhance situational awareness for individuals with hearing impairment by integrating environmental sound recognition, sound source localization, and real-time speech-to-text transcription within a unified framework. Unlike conventional assistive technologies that focus on sound amplification, the proposed system transforms acoustic signals into meaningful semantic and spatial information, enabling users to better interpret and respond to their surroundings. %The system architecture, including hardware integration and software design, was detailed, along with the implementation of key modules such as sound source localization.
Experimental investigations demonstrated the feasibility of operation on an embedded platform and highlighted the effectiveness of combining multiple audio understanding tasks within a single assistive solution. The integration of augmented reality visual feedback and haptic alerts enhances usability by providing intuitive, multimodal interaction. Building on this, the proposed system can be extended to AR lenses and evaluated with hearing-impaired individuals while incorporating user feedback. Additionally, a mobile application can be developed to receive vibration signals, control visualization settings, and integrate features such as text-to-speech to enable communication between deaf individuals and others. Moreover, speech-to-text performance can be improved in accuracy and latency through data collection and fine-tuning, resulting in a more effective and reliable system.

